'''Wakae Kagami Shrine''' (わかえかがみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Wakaeminami-chō, {{ill|lt=Higashiōsaka|Q243863|WD=Q243863|1=Higashiōsaka}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Main deities - Ōikazuchi Ōkami, {{ill|lt=Emperor Chūai|Q179971|WD=Q179971|1=Emperor Chūai}}
* Associated hall deity - {{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}}

=== History ===
Its founding year is unknown. In the section for the fourth month of {{ill|lt=Saikō|Q1324664|WD=Q1324664|1=Saikō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=854|Q24981|WD=Q24981|1=854}}) in the '{{ill|lt=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|Q1052905|WD=Q1052905|1=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku}}', there is a record of advancing divine rank to "Junior Fifth Rank Lower for Ōikazuchi-Hoake-no-Myojin of {{ill|lt=Kawachi Province|Q1047150|WD=Q1047150|1=Kawachi Province}}," thought to refer to Wakae Kagami Shrine. This shrine is also listed in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}', compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō (era)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Enchō|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}).

Because {{ill|lt=Wakae Castle|Q11616583|WD=Q11616583|1=Wakae Castle}} stood north of the enshrined site, it was revered by successive castle lords from {{ill|lt=Hatakeyama Masanaga|Q5680891|WD=Q5680891|1=Hatakeyama Masanaga}} to {{ill|lt=Miyoshi Yoshitsugu|Q986767|WD=Q986767|1=Miyoshi Yoshitsugu}}.

During the {{ill|lt=Summer Siege of Osaka|Q475780|WD=Q475780|lt=Osaka Campaign|1=Siege of Osaka}} in {{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|WD=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 20 ({{ill|lt=1615|Q6784|WD=Q6784|1=1615}}), it was struck by military fire in the {{ill|lt=Battle of Yao and Wakae|Q10892144|WD=Q10892144|lt=Battle of Wakae|1=Battle of Yao (1615)}} on May 6, and shrine buildings and treasures burned.

In {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}} 11 ({{ill|lt=1828|Q7570|WD=Q7570|1=1828}}) of the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, the honden was rebuilt.

In {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5) it was ranked {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}, and in January {{ill|lt=1908|Q2056|WD=Q2056|1=1908}} (Meiji 41) it was designated a shrine receiving offerings of sacred food and silk.

=== Precinct ===
* Honden (Higashiōsaka City designated {{ill|lt=tangible cultural property|Q2901860|WD=Q2901860|1=Tangible Cultural Property (Japan)}}) - rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}} 11 ({{ill|lt=1828|Q7570|WD=Q7570|1=1828}}). Valuable as shrine architecture from the {{ill|lt=Bunka-Bunsei period|Q11435433|WD=Q11435433|lt=Bunka-Bunsei era|1=Ōgosho period}}. It has an unusual structure with an associated hall inserted between two ikken-sha {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} halls.
* Haiden
* Shrine office
* Kagami-zuka - said to be where {{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}} stopped on her return from {{ill|lt=Conquest of the Three Han|Q11249435|WD=Q11249435|1=Three Han Campaign}} and buried a mirror.
* Distant worship site

